Why ISIS has been able to persist
New York—İstanbul, Dhaka and Baghdad's deadly terrorist attacks show that the reach of the Islamic State (ISIS) has extended to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East and parts of Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terror network will be able to carry out such mass killings.
But ISIS is not particularly hard to eradicate.
The issue is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not treated ISIS as a primary enemy.
This point should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force. The United States estimates that it has between 20,000 to 25,000 members in Iraq and Syria, and about 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military forces of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is nothing compared to these numbers.
In September 2014, President Obama of the United States pledged to "strike and ultimately destroy" ISIS. However, the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (in the background), have been focused on undermining President Bashar al-Assad of Syria.
Recently, Major General Herzi Halevy of the Israeli army openly stated (as reported by a journalist present at Halevy's speech): "Israel does not want to see the Syrian situation end with ISIS being defeated, superpowers withdrawing from the region, and Israel facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but Israel's greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two main quasi-military adversaries — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad, rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the United States, the Syrian war is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told General Wesley Clark of the U.S. Army:
"But we (from the Gulf War) did learn one thing, that we can use force in the region — — in the Middle East — — and the Soviets will not stop us."
In the next superpower challenging us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regimes — — Syria, Iran (as written), Iraq."
The multiple wars the United States has waged in the Middle East — — Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. — — were to get the Soviet Union and later Russia out of the competition, allowing the United States to dominate alone."
These "efforts" were惨败.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the main goal is to overthrow Assad to weaken Iran."
Syria is part of a large-scale proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which is being fought in Syria and Yemen, and also at the more intense frontlines of Shia-Sunni confrontation in Bahrain and other countries in the region with separatist tendencies (including Saudi Arabia itself).
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional standing.
But Turkey now faces three adversaries along its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But terrorist attacks in Turkey orchestrated by ISIS may change this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for quasi-military operations.
However, both countries have expressed willingness to cooperate with the United States in fighting ISIS, and can also cooperate on resolving other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent, as its focus is on ousting Assad.
The U.S. foreign policy community condemns Russian President Putin for supporting Assad, while Russia condemns the United States for attempting to overthrow Assad.
These complaints may seem contradictory, but in reality, they are not.
The U.S. and its allies' attempts to topple Assad violate the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense as stipulated by the Charter.
Granted, Assad is a tyrant, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The persistent existence of ISIS highlights three major strategic flaws in U.S. foreign policy, as well as a fatal tactical flaw.
First, the new conservatism, which demands the achievement of U.S. hegemony through regime change, is not only ignorant of bloody-minded thinking; it is also classic imperial overreach.
Everywhere the U.S. has attempted such a thing, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has long funded secret operations through Saudi Arabia to arm and train Sunni jihadists.
In turn, these jihadists gave rise to ISIS, which is the same direct (perhaps unintended) consequence of the policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, the United States largely viewing Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies is to a large extent an outdated self-fulfilling prophecy.
Rebuilding relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, at the tactical level, the United States' attempt to fight a dual front war against Assad and ISIS has failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the Nusrah Front (al-Nusira Front), will fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide aerial cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies will be able to defeat ISIS.
Undoubtedly, Assad will continue to rule; undoubtedly, Russia will remain an ally of Syria; undoubtedly, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for some time still under the banner of ISIS; but the organization will be expelled from its bases of operation in Syria and Iraq.
This result not only can eradicate ISIS on the Middle Eastern land; but also lay the foundation for a more comprehensive缓解 of regional tensions.
The United States and Russia can begin to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
(It would also be beneficial if NATO commits not to allow Ukraine's membership or to escalate the ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe.)
There are other benefits.
Adopting a cooperative approach to combat ISIS will give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to seek new pragmatic arrangements with Iran.
The security of Israel can be strengthened by allowing Iran to develop cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with the West, thereby increasing the chances of delayed Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the strategic weaknesses of the West — especially the United States — today.
The West is capable of defeating ISIS.
The issue lies in whether the United States will undertake the strategic reassessment needed to achieve this goal.
